{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775886989133,"sessionID":"ses_284e35be5ffeSpJnNdJ6WYDdHX","part":{"id":"prt_d7b1cf709001FRY72jFi7khYhC","messageID":"msg_d7b1cf023001C2PvQkTkEWRSWx","sessionID":"ses_284e35be5ffeSpJnNdJ6WYDdHX","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-e352154fa5334b04ab396e12b2fec6c9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Proposal: AR-029 — SDK HTTP 底层客户端\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: \n5: AR-029 aims to implement and standardize the HTTP client layer for the AgentCube Python SDK. This layer provides the underlying HTTP communication infrastructure for:\n6: - Control plane operations (session creation/deletion via Workload Manager)\n7: - Data plane operations for Code Interpreter (command execution, file operations)\n8: - Data plane operations for Agent Runtime (payload invocation)\n9: \n10: The HTTP client layer ensures consistent request/response handling, connection pooling, timeout management, and session header management across all SDK clients.\n11: \n12: ## Scope\n13: \n14: ### In Scope\n15: 1. **Control Plane Client (`ControlPlaneClient`)**\n16:    - HTTP client for Workload Manager interactions\n17:    - Session lifecycle: create and delete Code Interpreter sessions\n18:    - Authentication via Bearer token (auth_token argument or K8s SA token file)\n19:    - Connection pooling with configurable pool settings\n20: \n21: 2. **Code Interpreter Data Plane Client (`CodeInterpreterDataPlaneClient`)**\n22:    - HTTP client for Router-based Code Interpreter operations\n23:    - Command execution (shell commands, code execution)\n24:    - File operations: write, upload, download, list\n25:    - Session header: `x-agentcube-session-id`\n26:    - Base URL construction from router_url + namespace + cr_name\n27: \n28: 3. **Agent Runtime Data Plane Client (`AgentRuntimeDataPlaneClient`)**\n29:    - HTTP client for Router-based Agent Runtime operations\n30:    - Session bootstrapping via GET on invocation endpoint\n31:    - Payload invocation via POST\n32:    - Session header: `x-agentcube-session-id`\n33:    - Base URL construction from router_url + namespace + agent_name\n34: \n35: 4. **HTTP Session Utilities**\n36:    - `create_session()`: Creates `requests.Session` with connection pooling\n37:    - `read_token_from_file()`: Reads auth token from K8s SA token path\n38:    - Timeout configuration: default read timeout 120s, connect timeout 5.0s\n39: \n40: 5. **Exception Hierarchy**\n41:    - Base exception: `AgentCubeError`\n42:    - `CommandExecutionError`: For non-zero exit codes\n43:    - `SessionError`: For session management failures\n44:    - `DataPlaneError`: For data plane operation failures\n45: \n46: ### Out of Scope\n47: - High-level client logic (context managers, retry policies, automatic reconnection)\n48: - WebSocket or streaming communication\n49: - API version negotiation beyond v1 paths\n50: - TLS/certificate configuration beyond default `requests` behavior\n51: \n52: ## Impact Analysis\n53: \n54: ### Positive Impact\n55: 1. **Consistency**: Single HTTP client implementation pattern across all SDK clients\n56: 2. **Performance**: Connection pooling reduces connection overhead\n57: 3. **Reliability**: Configurable timeouts prevent hanging requests\n58: 4. **Maintainability**: Centralized HTTP logic makes updates easier\n59: 5. **Testing**: Clear separation allows mocking HTTP clients in tests\n60: \n61: ### Dependencies\n62: - `requests` library (>= 3.0)\n63: - `PyJWT` (>= 2.0.0)\n64: - `cryptography`\n65: - Python >= 3.10\n66: \n67: ### Breaking Changes\n68: None. This is a new module implementation.\n69: \n70: ### Compatibility\n71: - Backward compatible with existing SDK public API (`CodeInterpreterClient`, `AgentRuntimeClient`)\n72: - Environment variables: `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL`, `ROUTER_URL` for default configuration\n73: - K8s SA token path: `/var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token`\n74: \n75: ## Alternatives Considered\n76: \n77: ### Alternative 1: Use `httpx` instead of `requests`\n78: **Pros**:\n79: - Async support built-in\n80: - HTTP/2 support\n81: - Modern API design\n82: \n83: **Cons**:\n84: - Additional dependency\n85: - Less mature ecosystem compared to requests\n86: - Would require learning curve for maintainers\n87: \n88: **Decision**: Stick with `requests` due to maturity and broader adoption in Python ecosystem.\n89: \n90: ### Alternative 2: Separate configuration dataclass for HTTP settings\n91: **Pros**:\n92: - Centralized configuration management\n93: - Easier to override defaults consistently\n94: \n95: **Cons**:\n96: - Adds indirection and complexity\n97: - Current per-client constructor approach is simpler\n98: - No clear benefit for the limited number of HTTP settings\n99: \n100: **Decision**: Keep configuration distributed across client constructors for simplicity and explicitness.\n101: \n102: ### Alternative 3: Auto-retry on transient failures\n103: **Pros**:\n104: - Improved resilience in production environments\n105: - Handles temporary network issues\n106: \n107: **Cons**:\n108: - Adds complexity to HTTP client layer\n109: - Retry logic is application-specific\n110: - Could mask underlying issues\n111: \n112: **Decision**: Defer retry logic to higher-level clients or application code; keep HTTP layer simple and predictable.\n113: \n114: ## Implementation Plan\n115: \n116: ### Phase 1: Core HTTP Utilities\n117: - Implement `create_session()` with connection pooling\n118: - Implement `read_token_from_file()`\n119: - Implement exception hierarchy\n120: \n121: ### Phase 2: Control Plane Client\n122: - Implement `ControlPlaneClient` with Workload Manager endpoints\n123: - Add auth token resolution (argument → K8s SA token → none)\n124: - Implement `create_session()` and `delete_session()`\n125: \n126: ### Phase 3: Code Interpreter Data Plane Client\n127: - Implement base URL construction logic\n128: - Implement all file operations (write, upload, download, list)\n129: - Implement command execution with timeout handling\n130: - Add session header management\n131: \n132: ### Phase 4: Agent Runtime Data Plane Client\n133: - Implement session bootstrapping via GET\n134: - Implement `invoke()` with POST payload\n135: - Add session header management\n136: \n137: ### Phase 5: Integration\n138: - Update `CodeInterpreterClient` to use new HTTP clients\n139: - Update `AgentRuntimeClient` to use new HTTP clients\n140: - Add unit tests for all HTTP clients\n141: - Add integration tests with mock servers\n142: \n143: ## Success Criteria\n144: \n145: 1. All HTTP clients pass unit tests with 100% coverage\n146: 2. Integration tests demonstrate successful:\n147:    - Session creation and deletion via Control Plane\n148:    - Code execution and file operations via Code Interpreter Data Plane\n149:    - Agent invocation via Agent Runtime Data Plane\n150: 3. No breaking changes to public API\n151: 4. Documentation updated for new HTTP client classes\n152: 5. Performance benchmarks show connection pooling reduces overhead\n\n(End of file - total 152 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Proposal: AR-029 — SDK HTTP 底层客户端\n\n## Purpose\n\nAR-029 aims to implement and standardize the HTTP client layer for the AgentCube Python SDK. This layer provides the underlying HTTP communication infrastructure for:\n- Control plane operations (session creation/deletion via Workload Manager)\n- Data plane operations for Code Interpreter (command execution, file operations)\n- Data plane operations for Agent Runtime (payload invocation)\n\nThe HTTP client layer ensures consistent request/response handling, connection pooling, timeout management, and session header management across all SDK clients.\n\n## Scope\n\n### In Scope\n1. **Control Plane Client (`ControlPlaneClient`)**\n   - HTTP client for Workload Manager interactions\n   - Session lifecycle: create and delete Code Interpreter sessions\n   - Authentication via Bearer token (auth_token argument or K8s SA token file)\n   - Connection pooling with configurable pool settings\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775886989113,"end":1775886989130}}}}
